# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] Louis Maroons** baseball team finished with a 94–19 record and won the championship of the new Union Association (UA).
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] After the season, the UA folded and the Maroons joined the National League; they were the only UA team to continue past the 1884 season.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] To this day, the Maroons' .832 winning percentage hasn't been matched by a professional baseball team.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] Louis Maroons are not usually mentioned in the conversation of baseball teams with the best single-season records of all time.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] This team also set the record for the best start to a season in baseball history, going 20–0 before losing 8–1 to the Boston Reds on May 24, in their 21st game of the season.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] The Maroons scored 887 runs while allowing 429, for a run differential of +458, the best in major-league history, as records and statistics of the UA are recognized by Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] The team was back in the news in 2015, when the Golden State Warriors started the 2015–16 season with an NBA-record 24 straight wins; this surpassed the Maroons' 20–0 start, which was previously the record for the four major professional sports leagues in the United States.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1885-st-louis-maroons-season] Louis Maroons season** was the team's first season in the National League after winning the Union Association championship in 1884.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1885-st-louis-maroons-season] This season was not nearly as successful, as the Maroons finished with a 36–72 record, worst in the eight-team league.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1886-st-louis-maroons-season] Louis Maroons** finished with a 43–79 record in the National League, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1886-st-louis-maroons-season] After the season, the team was purchased by John T.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1886-st-louis-maroons-season] Brush and moved to Indianapolis, becoming the **Hoosiers**.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1887-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] The **1887 Indianapolis Hoosiers** finished with a 37–89 record in the National League, finishing in last place in their first season in Indianapolis.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1887-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] They had played the previous three seasons in St.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1887-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] Following the 1886 season, the Maroons franchise was purchased by the National League and subsequently sold to John T.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1887-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] On March 8, the Hoosiers additionally purchased a number of players who were under league control.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1887-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] Technically, these players were purchased from the Maroons franchise.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1887-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] Among these players were Henry Boyle, John Cahill, Jerry Denny, Jack Glasscock, Egyptian Healy, John Kirby, Jack McGeachey, George Myers, Otto Schomberg, and Emmett Seery.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1888-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] The **1888 Indianapolis Hoosiers** finished with a 50–85 record in the National League, finishing in seventh place.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1888-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] October 20, 1887: Gid Gardner and cash were traded by the Hoosiers to the Washington Nationals for Paul Hines.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1889-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1889 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 19th season of the franchise.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1889-boston-beaneaters-season] The team finished second in the National League.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] The **1889 Indianapolis Hoosiers** finished with a 59–75 record in the National League, finishing in seventh place.
[src:1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season/1889-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] The team folded after the season concluded.
